7":"1587","1583":"1583","Of, Kidderminister, Worcs, Eng":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bowyer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a maker or seller of bows, or an archer, from Middle English <i>bowyere</i>, an agent derivative of Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow’. Compare   Bowman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowman","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for an archer, hunter or soldier armed with a bow, from Middle English <i>bow(e)man</i>, <i>bouman</i> (from Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’). This word was distinguished from   Bowyer  , which denoted a maker or seller of bows.","Americanized form of German   Baumann   or the Dutch cognate   Bouwman  ."]},{"name":"Bouyer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Frederique, Monique, Napoleon.","English: variant of   Bowyer  .","French (southern): regional variant of   Bouvier  . Compare   Beyea  ."]},{"name":"Boyers","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Bowyer  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Joyce Bowyer was born in 1587, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. She married Anthony Bowyer in 1610. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1587–":"1587–Surnud","1583–Male":"1583–Surnud","1612–1679":"1612–1679","1587–Female":"1587–Surnud","1679":"1679","1612":"1612","1610":"1610","29 JUN 1612":"29. juuni 1612","1587":"1587","1583":"1583","Of, Kidderminister, Worcs, Eng":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1587–":"1587–Kuollut","1583–Male":"1583–Kuollut","1612–1679":"1612–1679","1587–Female":"1587–Kuollut","1679":"1679","1612":"1612","1610":"1610","29 JUN 1612":"29. kesäkuuta 1612","1587":"1587","1583":"1583","Of, Kidderminister, Worcs, Eng":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, England":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1587–":"1587–Décédée","1583–Male":"1583–Décédé","1612–1679":"1612–1679","1587–Female":"1587–Décédée","1679":"1679","1612":"1612","1610":"1610","29 JUN 1612":"29 juin 1612","1587":"1587","1583":"1583","Of, Kidderminister, Worcs, Eng":"Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Joyce Bowyer est née en 1587, à Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Anthony Bowyer en 1610. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1587–":"1587–Verstorben","1583–Male":"1583–Verstorben","1612–1679":"1612–1679","1587–Female":"1587–Verstorben","1679":"1679","1612":"1612","1610":"1610","29 JUN 1612":"29. Juni 1612","1587":"1587","1583":"1583","Of, Kidderminister, Worcs, Eng":"Worcestershire, Englan